snippet.textDisplay:
Rest in peace, Mac. Fate hits at the worst moment sometimes. You just wanted to relax after another day in this reality, but never woke up again after. Everyone can relate to you because each one of us can feel down once in a while, although some more than others. I feel like life is constantly trying to find a balance around it's mean, so we've got to accept: the good can only come to us if the times can also be bad for a while. No ups without the downs, otherwise life would just progress in a numb, straight line. We're only sad because someone who was changing the world for the better, had to go whilst having so much more to say. We won't be able to enjoy your company for a while, but the impact your life had on the world will go on. So until the place and comes in which every one of us is destined to go to after we die, we'll keep on going just as you taught us to do.


Much appreciation,
A fan

snippet.textDisplay: I use to listen to mac in call of duty MW2 days, I was a teenager, there wasnt any real stress, mac was used on most of my COD videos, his music was a big part of my life as a kid. I grew up and stopped listening to mac, then last year I was in a dark place, it took a lot of people to get me the help I needed, and threw this last year I went back to mac, but as an adult, and as someone in desperate need of help. Swimming has been played near enough every day for the last year. As a kid and as an adult, this man has helped me. The best part about coming back to his music... there's so much mac music I haven't even heard yet, each month I'm getting closer to the light, with a whole lot of mac helping me through, I hope his family know the extent of how his music has helped people and how it always will.
